(537, 1, '2014-05-06 05:00:29', '2014-05-06 09:00:29', 'How many calls a day go to your voice mail? Probably a lot, so why not get creative with it?\r\n\r\n<iframe src="//fast.wistia.net/embed/iframe/f7gr8dp6ru?videoFoam=true" allowtransparency="true" frameborder="0" scrolling="no" class="wistia_embed" name="wistia_embed" allowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen webkitallowfullscreen oallowfullscreen msallowfullscreen width="640" height="360"></iframe><script src="//fast.wistia.net/assets/external/iframe-api-v1.js"></script>\r\n\r\nWe all have and use voice mail. Think about how many times a day you allow a call to go to your voice mail. I think if we''re honest with ourselves, there''s many of us that always let an inbound call go to voice mail first to screen it. Well with that in mind, why not get creative with it? This week Rick Floyd touches on a chapter in the Little Red Book of Selling by Jeffrey Gitomer that talks about just that - getting creative with your voice mail.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://www.gitomer.com/Jeffrey-Gitomer-Little-Red-Book-of-Selling-pluLRB.html" target="_blank"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-511" alt="Little Red Book" src="http://chasingexcellenceblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Little-Red-Book.jpg" width="128" height="192" /></a>If you think about it, you typical voice mail greeting lasts about 15 to 30 seconds. Well rather than have your caller listen to your typical greeting, why not create a greeting that asks for the business, or promotes a new product. Not only that, but why not change it regularly promoting other products or asking for referrals?\r\n\r\nTune in to today''s show and let Rick explain it to you, you''ll be glad you did! Please remember to leave you comments down below and share this post with others you feel will like it!\r\n\r\nHave a great week.\r\n\r\nRick Floyd', 'Being Creative with Your Voice Mail', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'being-creative-with-your-voice-mail', '', '', '2014-05-06 01:27:02', '2014-05-06 05:27:02', '', 0, 'http://chasingexcellenceblog.com/?p=537', 0, 'post', '', 1),
